Comparitive Analysis of Crime in New York and Los Angeles¶

CMSC320 Final Project Hana Chitsaz, Vrunda Jasani, Sukhman Kaur

An Analysis of East Coast vs West Coast Criminal Data
 Crime in Los Angeles and New York (2010-2019)

Our Project In our course, CMSC320, we were able to create a final project on a topic of our choosing. We chose two separate datasets: Los Angeles and New York City. We decided to choose these locations as they are very popular cities on both the East and West coasts. In fact, they are the largest city on each coast (population-wise). We were able to find very large datasets that contained a lot of information about the different crimes that occurred throughout both locations and compare and contrast the information we found.

Data Sets: The following are the links to the New York City and LA datasets that we used:

New York City: https://data.cityofnewyork.us/Public-Safety/NYPD-Complaint-Data-Historic/qgea-i56i LA: https://data.lacity.org/Public-Safety/Crime-Data-from-2010-to-2019/63jg-8b9z

The New York City dataset contained over 7 million entries of data from 2006 to 2019. The Los Angeles dataset contained over 2 million entries of data from 2010-2019.

What Did We Do:

We were able to apply the skills we learned throughout this course to read, tidy, analyze, and compare and contrast our datasets. For this project, we were looking at multiple datasets to compare and contrast the information. We referred to the following link: https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/comparison-of-two-data-sets-using-python-a24a6d8beb13 to get some tips on how to look and compare two sets of data. We also used many resources such as https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/user_guide/visualization.html and https://python-visualization.github.io/folium/ to create graphs and other visualizations to portray and show our analysis of the datasets. We used these resources as well as what we learned in class and through past projects to create our tutorial through the data science pipeline.

The first step is to import any and all required libraries. Here we import folium a library used to create convenient map API and the numpy and pandas library in order to use the numpy and pandas database functions which makes modifying, adjusting, and comparing the datasets much easier.

I have downloaded the csv file and uploaded them to Jupyter notebook so that we can read the file into a pandas data table using the pandas read_csv function.

Data Processing¶

Now we want to clean up the database so that we are only looking at data from the years 2010 to 2019 since our more restricted data set (the LA dataset) only has dates from 2010-2019. This way we will be comparing data from both sides of the coast during the same time period.

Let's start with LA. Although the data provided is from 2010-2019, we will run through the process of cleaning the dates for future use and in order to be extra careful. Here we run into one issue: the date and time are grouped into one column. We will split this column into day and month, year, and time.

Here we are parsing the column in the LA dataset using the str.split function and appending the time and whether it occured in the AM or PM together into a new time column in the database.

# Text wrapping for the x lable of the graph

import textwrap
def wrap_labels(axs, width, break_long_words=False):
    labels = []
    for label in axs.get_xticklabels():
        text = label.get_text()
        labels.append(textwrap.fill(text, width=width,
                      break_long_words=break_long_words))
    axs.set_xticklabels(labels, rotation=0)

# plotting bar graph of Top 10 ofenses in New York.

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


# Getting the list of all the crimes as x value and the number of each crime committed as y value
y = ny['OFNS_DESC'].value_counts().tolist()[0:9]
x = ny['OFNS_DESC'].value_counts().index.tolist()[0:9]



fig, axs = plt.subplots(figsize = (15, 9))
plot = sns.barplot(x, y, palette = 'magma')

axs.set_title('Top 10 OFENSES IN NEW YORK', color = 'b', fontsize = 13, weight = 'bold')
axs.set_xlabel('OFENSES', color = 'b', fontsize = 12)
axs.set_ylabel('NUMBER OF OFENSES', color = 'b', fontsize = 12)

# wrapping the text for x labels.

Here we are using the folium library to create interactive maps. These maps show the clustering of homicides with female victims over the past three years. The benefit of using a map to display this data as opposed to a bar graph, pie chart, or scatter plot is that the map allows the user to see clusters of occurrences that happened in different locations around the city in a cleaner way than if we had just listed the addresses or area codes. The red markers indicate homicides with female victims that happened in 2019, and blue and green indicate the same for 2018 and 2017, respectively. Another benefit of using the map to display and analyze this data is that the user can zoom in or out of different areas of interest on the map, depending on what you are trying to learn from the data. For example, if you want to see an overview or get a general idea of where most homicides occur with female victims in La, you look at the zoomed out version of the map. However, after seeing the cluster of homicides in the mid to southern area of LA, you have the ability to zoom in and get a better understanding of what years homicides were most common and in what areas. In this case, 2018 had the most homicides with female victims, and from the map you can see a cluster of almost entirely 2018 homicides in South Los Angeles. Similarly for the NYC dataset, the map shows clusters of where the homicides occur and what areas with what years were most common. For example, south NYC saw much less homicides in 2018 compared to 2019 and 2017.

Analysis and Hypothesis Testing¶

Now, we will perform hypothesis testing for LA and New York for crime rate vs years. We will first get the number for crimes for each year. Then I got the population of each city for ech year from the https://www.health.ny.gov/statistics/vital_statistics/2018/table02.htm. Then we divide the value of number of crimes for each year by the population of that year and multiply by 100 in order to obtain the crime rate. Then we plot those values and get a scatter plot with a regresion line.

In order to analyze year vs. crime, we decided to create a visual to show the different years vs. the number of crimes that were committed in LA. The x-axis represents the year that the crime was committed and the y axis represents the crime rate comitted in that year.

Null Hypothesis: There is a correlation between years and crime rate.

As we can see from the statistics above, we have a very large p value of 0.8122 which is 81.22%. In order to reject or accept the null hypothesis, we need look at how close it is to 0. The cutoff is 5% and our p value is well above that. Therefore, we will need to accept the null hypothesis which was that there is no correlation between year (time) and the number of crimes committed. We also printed it out and got the output "no correlation" which means that our null hypothesis was accepted. Therefore, we know that number of crimes that are reported in our data do not have any correlation with the year it is or as time goes up/down.

Limitations¶

One major limitation these datasets and our analysis has is the lack of evidence of causation. Our analysis looked at correlations and patterns observed, but does not dive into the possible causations of what the data recorded. This is incredibly important to note in data science: causation is NOT correlation. Another limitation we faced was dealing with missing or unknown data. For the most part, our analysis strayed away from dealing with any missing data. We were lucky that our dataset had data usually responsibly recorded. However, we did not use data that did not have a date and time recorded. Could there possibly be a correlation between not recorded date and time and certain crimes? Sure, but we did not choose to analyze that in our tutorial. Additionally, we looked at crimes that involved specific sexes. However, these datasets only acknowledged male and female sexes. Moreover, there were datasets that had sex listed as unknown. There are many ways of dealing with missing data. For more information visit the following links: http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/missing_data.html https://cmsc320.github.io/files/SAMHSA_missing_values.pdf

In our analysis we deemed it best not to take any averages or make predictions about that missing data, but to only use the information given to us.
